Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and hook into Shell's `Navigating` event (shell back button):

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating += OnShellNavigating;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating -= OnShellNavigating;
    }

    // Intercepts Shell's nav-bar back button
    private async void OnShellNavigating(object sender, ShellNavigatingEventArgs e)
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges || e.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
            return;

        var deferral = e.GetDeferral();

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave)
            e.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }

    // Intercepts Android/device hardware back button
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
            {
                _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            }
        });

        return true; // cancel the default navigation
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, hide the default back button and add your own toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
    <!-- ... -->
</ContentPage>
```

Or inline and more concisely:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        IconOverride=""
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

With the command in your view-model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand => new Command(async () =>
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes", "Discard changes?", "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!leave) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
});
```

**Key points:**
- **`e.GetDeferral()`** is essential — it lets you `await` the dialog before Shell commits the navigation.
- **`OnBackButtonPressed`** only fires for the device/hardware back button (mainly Android).
- **`BackButtonBehavior`** with a `Command` replaces the default Shell back-button tap, so the `Navigating` event won't fire for it — put your guard logic in the command itself.
